The paper deals with a scheduling problem, which is a classic topic in computer science and falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also introduces a geometric interpretation of scheduling, which suggests that it may belong to the category of computational geometry (cs.CG) or game theory (cs.GT). The paper uses randomized algorithms and approximation techniques, which are common in the category of theoretical computer science (cs.TH) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper involves optimization and numerical analysis, which are relevant to the categories of information theory (cs.IT) and numerical analysis (cs.NA).
